            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rohan Sharma\u2019s story began not in San Francisco, but in Fremont, amidst the hum of Silicon Valley and the high expectations of his Indian immigrant parents. They envisioned a son in engineering or medicine, a stable, lucrative path. Rohan, however, was drawn to the quiet, emotional landscapes of people. The catalyst for his unconventional career was his younger sister, Anjali, who battled a severe anxiety that left her withdrawn. He watched, fascinated and relieved, as she found a voice not in words, but in the vibrant chaos of her sketchbooks. This became his calling.\n\nDefying familial pressure, Rohan pursued a psychology degree at UC Davis before committing fully to a graduate program in Art Therapy and Counseling. It was a difficult conversation, but his parents\u2019 skepticism slowly softened as they saw the profound impact he had during his internships. He chose to build his life in San Francisco, drawn to its embrace of social services and its inherent creative spirit. He found a rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond, a perfect nexus between the city's energy and the tranquility of Golden Gate Park.\n\nNow at 40, Rohan\u2019s life is a study in purposeful routine. His 2.8-mile bicycle commute is a moving meditation, carrying him to the various contracts he serves across the city\u2014a public school in the Mission, a community health clinic in the Tenderloin, and a small senior center. He helps children process trauma through clay and guides adults toward self-discovery with paint. The work is emotionally demanding, and he recharges through long rides in the Presidio and by filling his own sketchbooks with cityscapes and portraits.\n\nHis social circle is small but deep, comprised of other therapists, artists, and friends met through a local cycling club. While dedicated to his clients, Rohan dreams of a more permanent impact. His ultimate aspiration is to open a non-profit, sliding-scale art therapy studio in his neighborhood, creating a dedicated safe haven for expression. For Rohan, San Francisco isn't just a home; it's the canvas on which he helps others paint their own stories of healing and hope."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 20, home from UC Davis for the weekend. Anjali had been silent and withdrawn all day. But on her bed, her sketchbook was open to a new drawing: a tangled, thorny forest with a tiny figure emerging into a sunlit clearing. The raw emotion on the paper was louder than any words. In that instant, he grasped that art wasn't a hobby; it was a language of survival. This silent confession set his entire life in motion.\n\n2.\nThe phone call he\u2019d always dreaded came when he was 25, interning at a family center. His parents had visited, stiffly observing his session. That night, his mother\u2019s voice was different\u2014soft, without its usual edge of concern. \u201cThe boy\u2019s mother said you gave her son his voice back,\u201d she said, the words heavy with discovery. The weight of their disappointment, a burden he\u2019d carried for years, finally dissolved. He felt not just acceptance, but pride.\n\n3.\nA seven-year-old at the Mission school, selectively mute after a trauma, had said nothing for weeks. Then one afternoon, eight years ago, Rohan watched him silently mash a block of gray clay. The boy finished, looked Rohan in the eye, and pointed to the two crude figures he\u2019d made. A story was told without a single word. It was a sacred, shattering moment of connection that renewed his belief in the profound power of his work.\n\n4.\nAt 27, keys in hand, he stood alone in his new, empty Inner Richmond apartment. The afternoon light streamed through the bay window, illuminating dust motes dancing in the air. He could smell the old wood floors and the faint scent of fog from the park. It was rent-controlled, a miracle. After years of fighting for his path, this space\u2014earned and chosen entirely by him\u2014felt like his first true exhale. This was his anchor.\n\n5.\nJust last year, at 39, he was cycling home up Clement Street after a draining day. He passed a dusty, vacant storefront, a \u201cFor Lease\u201d sign taped inside. He stopped, and suddenly he could see it all: the name on the window, the shelves of supplies, canvases drying on racks, warm light spilling onto the sidewalk. His abstract dream of his own non-profit became a tangible, solid goal on that street corner. The future suddenly had an address."
